The goal is `⊢ 0 ≤ ‖eval (↑q) (X - C lamb)‖`.

We need to show `0 ≤ ‖eval (↑q) (X - C lamb)‖`.

The expression `eval (↑q) (X - C lamb)` evaluates to `(q : ℂ) - lamb`.

So, we need to show `0 ≤ ‖(q : ℂ) - lamb‖`.

The complex norm `‖z‖` is defined as `Real.sqrt (z.re ^ 2 + z.im ^ 2)`. Since `Real.sqrt` is always non-negative for non-negative input (which `z.re ^ 2 + z.im ^ 2` is), `‖z‖ ≥ 0`.

In Lean, for any complex number `z`, `‖z‖` is `Complex.abs z`, and `Complex.abs z ≥ 0`.

The proof is simply applying the fact that `‖z‖ ≥ 0`.

